  footnotes: []
english:
  title: In Gaoping City
  author: Yu Sun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Gaoping City, small as a measuring cup,
    With barely ten households of smoke and hearth.
    I tend to my carriage, planning to stay
    Just one evening beneath its roof.

    Yet how can I leave my traveling banner?
    Like a merchant of the Western lands,
    Spies come with their report:
    Barbarian cavalry gather in the fields,
    Driving all their beasts before them,
    Endless hordes following in their wake.

    The city commander mans his post,
    Thin soldiers in rough formation,
    A handful of torn flags planted on walls,
    Broken drums between the battlements—
    As if to match the mighty foe,
    A monkey wrestling a tiger.

    Yet I, though merely a passing guest,
    Must share in the city's fate if it falls.
    I climb the wall against all reason,
    And ask the commander his strategy.
    He says: "I hold this ground alone,
    How can I claim to strike them down?"

    Gazing down a hundred paces,
    Their armored cavalry gleams in formation,
    While I carry no weapon in my pack—
    Alas, what use have I for arms?

    But thinking further on these raiders,
    They too once fled a stronger power,
    Bringing their families to this refuge,
    Looking to China as a father's land.
    Should they not seek their own survival
    Rather than recklessly invite destruction?

    When I report this to Guangning,
    They will come to bring us aid.
    Quiet deliberation yields the right path;
    Rash action invites only calamity.
    So I tell my traveling companions:
    My words carry truth and wisdom.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Gaoping: A city in northeastern China, historically a frontier garrison'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Western lands merchant: A reference to the danger and uncertainty faced by merchants in remote border regions'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Guangning: A major fortress and administrative center, representing the official military authority that could provide relief'
  - key: ''
    value: The poem reflects the poet's observation of frontier defense and his philosophical meditation on the nature of survival, power, and moral restraint during the Jurchen raids of the Ming period
